The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Gyanwant Singh has been appointed the deputy commissioner (detective department). He will replace Peeyush Pandey, who will join the intelligence branch as special superintendent. Ajoy Kumar, deputy commissioner (armed police), will replace Singh as deputy commissioner (central). P.K Sahai, inspector-general (armed police) has been promoted as additional director-general (modernisation and coordination). 

 Singapore Airlines has announced its revised flight schedule to and from Calcutta. On Tuesdays and Fridays, the flights will leave Calcutta at 11.50 pm and reach Singapore at 6.25 am the following days. On Sundays, the flights will leave at 12.10 am and reach Singapore at 6.40 am. Return flights ? on Tuesdays, Fridays and Saturdays ? will arrive at 10.35 pm.

 AMRI Hospitals will present a daylong symposium on spinal cord injuries on Saturday. It will be held at Hyatt Regency. 

 Two persons were arrested at a shop on BB Ganguly Street on Thursday on charges of trading in medicines without having a drug-licence.

 Kamarhati Jute Mill (in Khardah), which closed down on January 30 following worker? unrest, will reopen on Saturday, labour minister Moham- med Amin said on Friday. 

 Calcutta High Court on Friday asked the education department to ensure that penal actions are taken against students found guilty of ragging, drinking and doping on the premises of educational institutions. 

 Pradeep Das, a resident of Jadavpur, and his son were arrested on Thursday on charges of assaulting a BSNL officer, Partha Pratim Haldar. The assault seems to have been in reaction to the questions that Haldar asked the Dases at their residence before providing an Internet connection. Haldar later suffered a cardiac arrest.

 Transport minister Subhas Chakraborty said on Friday that the government was planning to provide medical insurance to transport workers. 

